english:
  title: On the Buddhist Doctrine of Fortune and Misfortune
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven's way bestows blessing upon the virtuous and calamity upon the licentious. The human way rewards the good and punishes the wicked. This is because the human heart harbors both crookedness and rectitude, and one's conduct contains both right and wrong—thus fortune and misfortune respond according to their kind. So the Book of Poetry says, "Seek blessing, yet not through cunning," and Confucius taught, "When one offends Heaven, there is nowhere left to pray." The noble man, in facing fortune and misfortune, need only rectify his heart and cultivate his person. Fortune need not be pursued to come of itself, nor must misfortune be fled to distance itself naturally. Hence it is said: the noble man may harbor lifelong concern, yet he knows no sudden calamity. Should misfortune come from without, he simply receives it with equanimity—as though cold and heat pass before him, and he remains untouched.

    But the Buddhists disregard whether a person's mind is crooked or straight, right or wrong. Instead they claim: those who turn to our Buddha may escape calamity and gain fortune. So even one who commits the ten grave evils, upon turning to Buddha, escapes—while even a person of integrity, should he refuse Buddha, cannot escape. Grant that their doctrine were not false; it still springs from selfish heart and not from universal principle. Such should be condemned. And consider: since Buddhism arose, millennia have passed. Yet even those most devoted to Buddha—such as Emperor Wu of Liang or Emperor Xianzong of Tang—could not escape early death. As Han Yu said, "The more diligently one serves Buddha, the shorter one's years become." Is this truth not profound and evident?
  footnotes:
    - 'The Ten Grave Evils (十惡) in Buddhist doctrine: killing, stealing, adultery, lying, harsh speech, divisive speech, frivolous speech, covetousness, anger, and false views.'
    - Emperor Wu of Liang (梁武帝, r. 502-549) was a devout patron of Buddhism who abdicated and spent his final years in a monastery.
    - Han Yu (韓退之, 768-824) was a celebrated Tang dynasty essayist and Confucian who famously opposed Buddhism.
    - The phrase "獲罪於天，無所禱也" is attributed to Confucius in the Analects and reflects the Confucian belief that Heaven's judgment cannot be swayed by prayer once one has committed grave transgressions.
